dictionary.origin: Old English rēad, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch rood and German rot, from an Indo-European root shared by Latin rufus, ruber, Greek eruthros, and Sanskrit rudhira ‘red’.

definitions.definition: of a colour at the end of the spectrum next to orange and opposite violet, as of blood, fire, or rubies.
definitions.example: her red lips

definitions.definition: communist or socialist (used especially during the Cold War with reference to the Soviet Union).
definitions.example: the era of nuclear anxiety, the red scare and covert CIA plots

definitions.definition: involving bloodshed or violence.
definitions.example: red battle stamps his foot and nations feel the shock

definitions.definition: (of a Xhosa) coming from a traditional tribal culture.
definitions.example: a red Xhosa wife spends several years in her mother-in-law's homestead

definitions.definition: red colour or pigment.
definitions.example: their work is marked in red by the teacher

definitions.definition: a red thing.
definitions.example: which dress - the black or the red?

definitions.definition: a communist or socialist.
the situation of owing money to a bank or making a loss in a business operation.
definitions.example: the company was £4 million in the red

dictionary.origin: early 18th century (in the sense ‘occupy the same space’): from medieval Latin coincidere, from co- ‘together with’ + incidere ‘fall upon or into’.

definitions.definition: occur at the same time.
definitions.example: publication is timed to coincide with a major exhibition

definitions.definition: correspond in nature; tally.
definitions.example: the interests of employers and employees do not always coincide

dictionary.origin: Old English leornian  ‘learn’ (in Middle English also ‘teach’), of West Germanic origin; related to German lernen, also to lore1.

definitions.definition: gain or acquire knowledge of or skill in (something) by study, experience, or being taught.
definitions.example: they'd started learning French

definitions.definition: teach (someone).
definitions.example: ‘That'll learn you,’ he chuckled

dictionary.translate: сходство, быть похожим на, напоминать что-то
dictionary.origin: Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French, from the verb resembler (see resemble).

definitions.definition: the state of resembling or being alike.
definitions.example: they bear some resemblance to Italian figurines

dictionary.origin: late 16th century: from French concis or Latin concisus, past participle of concidere ‘cut up, cut down’, from con- ‘completely’ + caedere ‘to cut’.

definitions.definition: giving a lot of information clearly and in a few words; brief but comprehensive.
definitions.example: a concise account of the country's history

dictionary.origin: late Middle English: from Old French prescis, from Latin praecis- ‘cut short’, from the verb praecidere, from prae ‘in advance’ + caedere ‘to cut’.

definitions.definition: marked by exactness and accuracy of expression or detail.
definitions.example: precise directions

dictionary.origin: mid 17th century (originally in the sense ‘having a special determining quality’): from late Latin specificus, from Latin species (see species).

definitions.definition: clearly defined or identified.
definitions.example: savings were made by increasing the electricity supply only until it met specific development needs

definitions.definition: relating to species or a species.
definitions.example: the differences between them can only be on the specific level

definitions.definition: (of a duty or a tax) levied at a fixed rate per physical unit of the thing taxed, regardless of its price.

of or denoting a number equal to the ratio of the value of some property of a given substance to the value of the same property of some other substance used as a reference, such as water, or of a vacuum, under equivalent conditions.
definitions.example: specific dielectric strength

definitions.definition: a medicine or remedy effective in treating a particular disease or part of the body.
definitions.example: he grasped at the idea as though she had offered him a specific for cancer

definitions.definition: a precise detail.
definitions.example: I wish I'd put more thought into the specifics

dictionary.origin: late Old English hwīt, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch wit and German weiss, also to wheat.

definitions.definition: of the colour of milk or fresh snow, due to the reflection of all visible rays of light; the opposite of black.
definitions.example: a sheet of white paper

definitions.definition: belonging to or denoting a human group having light-coloured skin (chiefly used of peoples of European extraction).
definitions.example: a white farming community

definitions.definition: counter-revolutionary or reactionary.
white colour or pigment.
definitions.example: garnet-red flowers flecked with white

definitions.definition: the visible pale part of the eyeball around the iris.
the outer part (white when cooked) which surrounds the yolk of an egg; the albumen.
a member of a light-skinned people, especially one of European extraction.
a white or cream butterfly which has dark veins or spots on the wings and can be a serious crop pest.
paint or turn (something) white.
definitions.example: your passion hath whited your face

dictionary.origin: Old English blæc, of Germanic origin.

definitions.definition: of the very darkest colour owing to the absence of or complete absorption of light; the opposite of white.
definitions.example: black smoke

definitions.definition: belonging to or denoting any human group having dark-coloured skin, especially of African or Australian Aboriginal ancestry.
definitions.example: black adolescents of Jamaican descent

definitions.definition: characterized by tragic or disastrous events; causing despair or pessimism.
definitions.example: five thousand men were killed on the blackest day of the war

definitions.definition: denoting a covert military procedure.
definitions.example: clearance for black operations came from the highest political level

definitions.definition: (of goods or work) not to be handled or undertaken by trade union members, especially so as to express support for an industrial dispute elsewhere.
definitions.example: the union declared the ship black

definitions.definition: black colour or pigment.
definitions.example: a tray decorated in black and green

definitions.definition: a member of a dark-skinned people, especially one of African or Australian Aboriginal ancestry.
the situation of not owing money to a bank or of making a profit in a business operation.
definitions.example: it is hoped the club will be back in the black by the end of the season

definitions.definition: blackcurrant cordial.
definitions.example: a rum and black

definitions.definition: make (something) black; blacken.
definitions.example: the house was pocked with bullet holes and blacked by smoke

definitions.definition: refuse to handle (goods), undertake (work), or have dealings with (a person or business) as a way of taking industrial action.
definitions.example: the union blacked the film because overtime was not being paid

dictionary.origin: late Middle English: of unknown origin.

definitions.definition: a long-bodied chiefly marine fish with a cartilaginous skeleton, a prominent dorsal fin, and toothlike scales. Most sharks are predatory, although the largest kinds feed on plankton, and some can grow to a large size.
a small SE Asian freshwater fish with a tail resembling that of a shark, popular in aquaria.
a light greyish-brown European moth, the male of which has pale silvery hindwings.
(typically of a man at a social gathering) be in active pursuit of a sexual partner.
definitions.example: as soon as he arrived he was sharking among the women
